{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622574"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:03:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:03:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16802"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16802"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9493"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76704"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9493"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16802"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62196"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5158"},{"type":"tags","id":"5163"},{"type":"tags","id":"10292"},{"type":"tags","id":"10482"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22425"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22784"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76704"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELevetiracetam is a commonly prescribed antiepileptic medication that has a unique mechanism of action compared to other drugs in its class.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of levetiracetam?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enhances GABA receptor function","Blocks T-type calcium channels","Inhibits glutamate release","Blocks voltage-gated sodium channels","Binds to synaptic vesicle protein 2A"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe mechanism of action of levetiracetam is not clearly understood, however it is thought to primarily work by \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinding to synaptic vesicle protein 2A (SV2A)\u003C/strong\u003E, which decreases neurotransmitter release from synaptic vesicles at presynaptic terminals. This unique mechanism distinguishes it from traditional antiepileptic drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhancing GABA receptor function\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action for benzodiazepines and barbiturates, not levetiracetam.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking T-type calcium channels\u003C/strong\u003E is how ethosuximide works in treating absence seizures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting glutamate release\u003C/strong\u003E may occur indirectly through SV2A binding, but this is not the primary mechanism of levetiracetam.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking voltage-gated sodium channels\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism for older antiepileptic drugs like carbamazepine and phenytoin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy binding to SV2A, levetiracetam reduces neurotransmitter release in a broad and non-specific manner, which explains its effectiveness against multiple types of seizures. It is proposed that levetiracetam does not this effect during normal neuronal signalling. These factors contribute to a favourable side effect profile compared to older antiepileptic drugs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Levetiracetam is proposed to act primarily by binding to synaptic vesicle protein 2A (SV2A) to reduce neurotransmitter release.","Levetiracetam is a broad-spectrum antiepileptic drug effective against both focal and generalised seizures.","Unlike many other antiepileptic drugs, levetiracetam does not act on sodium channels or GABA receptors."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62196"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16802"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62196"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T12:02:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T12:02:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9493"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76704"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","syno